Sum of Squares with R

Different ways of calculating sum of squares in R. Here are three ways of finding sum of squares (for Points) in R.

Using anova()

empty.model <- lm(Points ~ NULL, data = MiamiHeat)
anova(empty.model)

Find at least one other way of calculating Sum of Squres

This is the long way where we save every step of the process.

# finding the residuals
MiamiHeat$Residual <- resid(empty.model)
MiamiHeat$SqResidual <- MiamiHeat$Residual^2

head(select(MiamiHeat, Points, Residual, SqResidual))
sum(MiamiHeat$SqResidual)
## [1] 10484.7

You could also just combine all those steps into one line.

# combining all those steps into one line
sum(resid(empty.model)^2)
## [1] 10484.7

Pros and Cons of SS

What is good about SS?

  • The SS is minimized if the mean is the model.
  • Eventually if you square and sum up the residuals, thats gonna be cool. Other things are going to add up to SS, perfectly, like Pythagorean Theorem.

What is the problem with SS? (That is, why do we need Variance and Standard Deviation?)

  • It gets bigger with more data points.
  • Variance fixes SS because it doesnt get bigger just because you have more data points. Variance is bigger when the distribution is more spread out (aka it has more variation).
  • StDeviation also does not get bigger with more data points. StDeviation is bigger when the distribution is more spread out (aka it has more variation)
# Make a faceted histogram of Points by Win (winning games vs. losing games)
gf_histogram(~ Points, data = MiamiHeat, fill = "tomato", color = "black") %>%
  gf_facet_grid(Win ~ .)

# Bonus: Make a jitter plot of Points by Win
gf_jitter(Points ~ Win, data = MiamiHeat, color = "tomato", size = 4, alpha = .5, width = .2)

Wins and Losses are not that different in how variable those games are (maybe Wins are a little more spread out but not by much). But Wins have A WAY BIGGER SS. Why? There are more wins. More data points means more residuals. More residuals means more squared residuals. More squared residuals means a bigger sum of squares.
